{
    "analysis": "From the prior summary we confirmed metric and log telemetry are available for many Sock Shop services; trace and error_logs are empty. Distinct metric KPIs include cpu, diskio, latency-50, latency-90, mem, socket, workload, error. We must now follow threshold calculation -> data extraction -> metric analysis. Global thresholds (P95) per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) were computed earlier for the full series. Next we need to filter metric data to the incident window (2024-01-21 14:33:03 to 2024-01-21 15:03:03 UTC) and detect anomalies where KPI values exceed their global P95 (for KPIs where larger is worse). We'll aggregate anomaly counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, max value in window, P95, and a severity ratio (max_value / p95) per component-KPI to narrow candidate faulty components. We will inspect top candidates' raw rows in-window to validate consecutive faults. No traces available, so logs will be used after metrics narrow candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric dataframe cached in the kernel, do the following (keep outputs compact):\n1) Recompute global P95 for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series (do not filter by time). Output a small table of these P95 values (columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95), limit to top 50 rows.\n2) Filter the metric dataframe to the incident window: 2024-01-21 14:33:03 UTC through 2024-01-21 15:03:03 UTC (inclusive). Then for KPI names cpu, mem, diskio, latency-50, latency-90, socket, workload, error treat higher values as anomalies and detect rows where value >= p95. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count (number of rows in window exceeding p95), earliest_anomaly_ts (the earliest timestamp in window that breaches p95), max_value_in_window, p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95. Return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc, with those columns.\n3) For the top 3 pairs from step 2, return up to the first 10 metric rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, ts) within the incident window (to inspect whether anomalies are consecutive). If no anomalies are found for any pair, instead return the same aggregates but using threshold loosened to P90 (compute P90 globally and repeat steps). Keep all outputs textual and compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step summary: global P95 thresholds were computed per (cmdb_id,kpi_name). Within the incident window many services show their socket KPI exactly at P95 continuously starting at 2024-01-21 14:36:00+00:00, suggesting a system-wide socket-level saturation or limit being hit. Two localized spikes above P95 (severity_ratio > 1.5) were identified: shipping.cpu (first breach 14:42 UTC) and session-db.diskio (first breach 14:39 UTC). Trace and error_logs are empty, so we must rely on metrics + log.csv. To localize the root cause we need to (1) verify that the shipping.cpu and session-db.diskio anomalies are real consecutive faults (not isolated), (2) check whether log.error_count increased for these services or broadly across services coincident with socket anomalies (14:36 UTC), and (3) confirm whether the socket anomalies across services are simultaneous (same earliest timestamp) indicating a network/socket-level issue rather than many independent service faults. Based on current evidence, there are two candidate root causes: a system-wide socket saturation (network/socket error) starting ~14:36 UTC, and localized resource spikes (shipping CPU, session-db disk IO) later; the socket/system-level issue is a stronger candidate because it affects many services simultaneously. Still need concrete log evidence (error_count) and full in-window metric rows for the two spikes to decide the root cause confidently.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Do three compact checks using cached dataframes (keep outputs bounded):\n1) Return all metric rows within the incident window for shipping.cpu and for session-db.diskio (columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, ts). Return up to 50 rows per pair.\n2) From log.csv filtered to the incident window, aggregate log.error_count per cmdb_id: compute total_error_count (sum of value where log_name=='log.error_count'), max_error (max value), and earliest_error_ts (earliest ts where value>0). Return rows for all cmdb_id where total_error_count>0, sorted by total_error_count desc (limit 20). Also return a short list of cmdb_id values that have any log.error_count>0.\n3) For metric socket KPIs within the incident window, produce a compact table (columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count (value>=global_p95), earliest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window) for all cmdb_id that have a socket KPI. Limit to top 50 rows. Additionally return the set of distinct earliest_anomaly_ts values seen for socket KPIs (to check simultaneity).\nKeep outputs textual and compact."
}

The analysis indicates a system-wide socket saturation starting at ~14:36 UTC; among the candidate services, the user service shows persistent socket anomalies and is the primary suspected root cause component.

